<font color="#FF0000">DR.  SPATZ</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 26  0:18:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I am a Viet-Nam Vet and proud to stand and say I put my life on the line because my country asked.  It changed my life forever and it hurt.<br><br>
I will not sit idle and listen to the war protester smuggly say they were right.  You do not know how it feels to be in a war zone and realize it is wrong and listen to your peers condem you while your there, while the enemy tries to kill you, and you only try to stay sane and alive until you can go home only to be condemnned when you get there.   FUCK-YOU you self righteous asshole.  Thanks for the opportunity to say that...it felt good.<br><br>
I will also not sit idle and listen to a Viet-Nam vet condem the war protestor for I also protested the war.  Who in their right mind would not condemn war.  <br><br>
We all must live with our little piece of hell wether we feel guilty because we went or we feel guilty because we came home or we feel guilty because we did not go.  America is a better place because of Viet-Nam.  I feel proud when I see the Viet-Nam veterans in leadership roles.  They speak with the wisdom learned on the battle field.<br><br>
So I live for all those soldiers who died, my life is dedicated to them.  Because I believe our country stands for honor, justice, equality, and compassion and anyone who dies for these ideals are hero's.  If my country asks me to stand again I will.  I only ask that my country stands for me and it will because it stands for honor, justice, equality, and compassion even if the current leaders may not.<br><br>

<p><code>--   (Steven Lane) </code><p>


